<TEXT>
the chinese sturgeon a 10foot ocean fish is in 
danger of extinction because a yangtze river dam is blocking it from 
the breeding grounds it has used for 300 million years an official 
newspaper reported today 
the china daily said the number of mature chinese sturgeons 
known scientifically as acipenser sinensis gray has fallen to 5000 
and at least 400 are being killed each year 
there are even fewer of the smaller white sturgeon it said 
the fish which weigh between 330 and 550 pounds when they lay 
eggs are unable to reach their breeding grounds in the upper 
reaches of the yangtze because of the newly completed gezhouba dam 
in central chinas hubei province 
the dam under construction since 1974 and partially operating 
since 1981 prevents the fish from reaching 19 of their 20 breeding 
grounds 1800 miles upstream in the jinsha river a yangtze 
tributary 
the dam builders originally agreed to put in a passageway for the 
fish around the dam but abandoned the idea because of the expense 
every year about 30 dead sturgeons are found at the base of the dam 
the newspaper quoted ke fuen director of the yangtze river 
aquatic products research institute as saying female sturgeons 
reach maturity at age 13 or 14 when they begin their 20month 
journey into chinas largest river 
because the fish eat nothing while they are in the river they 
are exhausted by the trip and are not ready to breed again for four 
or five years 
an average sturgeon he said lays about 18 pounds of eggs or 
about 450000 fry but 80 percent are eaten by other fish and most 
of the young sturgeon do not survive their sixmonth journey to the 
sea 
ke said about 370 sturgeon a year are caught at the mouth of the 
river by fishermen unaware the fish is now under state protection 
kes institute which has a budget of only 6750 a year for 
sturgeon research is now trying artificial breeding to save the 
fish from extinction it has been putting about 350000 sturgeon fry 
into the river a year 
the dam with a designed capacity of 27 million kilowatts will 
supply 20 percent of the central china networks electricity when it 
is fully operating 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

