<TEXT>
the defense department in a test program 
ordered by congress has begun reimbursing some of the expenses of 
activeduty servicemen who adopt children 
the unusual program which provides up to 2000 to offset the 
expenses of legally adopting a child is set to last through the end 
of the current fiscal year or until sept 30 unless congress 
votes to make the benefit permanent 
the adoption reimbursement program was formally launched by the 
pentagons personnel chief grant s green last september and as of 
dec 31 the army had processed 69 claims the air force and navy 
lagged behind the army in publishing their regulations and are only 
now handling claims 
the test was ordered in the pentagons fiscal 1988 budget bill 
and was championed by rep patricia schroeder dcolo 
it was proposed not only as a moralebuilding benefit that might 
play a role in keeping men and women in the military but also as a 
benefit for adoptive parents that parallels the cost of health care 
provided to women bearing babies in military hospitals 
the defense department nonetheless opposed the program arguing 
congress wasnt providing any extra money for the payments and it 
couldnt afford to tap other accounts 
in the current fiscal climate this program might negatively 
affect the other personnel and family initiatives that benefit a 
greater percentage of the military population the pentagon argued 
unsuccessfully 
the defense department has not requested any funding for the 
program in the fiscal 1990 budget pending before congress but 
promised it would look at the results of the test program to 
determine further action 
the reimbursement payments are available to anyone on active duty 
who initiates adoption proceedings after sept 30 1987 and 
before oct 1 1989 the pentagon regulation states 
benefits paid under the test program may be paid only after the 
adoption is final the adoption of stepchildren does not qualify for 
reimbursement under this program 
service members who adopt more than one child can claim a maximum 
5000 per year the regulation adds 
according to the national committee for adoption a group 
headquartered in washington the average agency adoption fee was 
about 6000 in 1987 
