the supreme court today turned away an appeal 
by northeastern states seeking to force the federal government to 
crack downn on acid rain and other pollution they say is caused by 
smokestacks in other states 
the court without comment refused to order the federal 
environmental protection agency to take steps to limit interstate 
air pollution 
the us circuit court of appeals here said last july 22 that the 
epa acted properly in dismissing bids by pennsylvania and maine 
officials to force federal action against pollution originating in 
other states 
the appeals court ordered the federal agency to restudy a 
petition by new york officials in light of newly available data 
officials from connecticut vermont new hampshire and new jersey 
joined those from maine and pennsylvania in asking the supreme court 
to overturn the appeals court ruling new york officials did not 
join the appeal to the high court 
the case acted on today stems from petitions filed with the epa 
in 1980 and 1981 by maine new york and pennsylvania claiming that 
soot smoke and sulfur dioxide were blowing in from hundreds of 
miles away 
they argued that pollutants from coalburning utility plants and 
factories in seven other states made it impossible for them to meet 
federal air quality standards 
the seven states complained about are illinois indiana 
kentucky michigan ohio tennessee and west virginia 
the northeastern states said federal law requires the epa to 
force the other states to revise their air pollution control plans 
federal clean air laws give the epa broad power to enforce state 
air quality programs if a states program is inadequate federal 
officials can order industries to clean up or face stiff fines or 
closing down operations 
but in the case acted on today epa officials said there was 
insufficient evidence to prove that air pollution in the northeast 
originated hundreds of miles away the agency also argued that 
federal law is not designed to cover such longrange pollution 
the appeals court here gave deference to the agencys expertise 
this court is being asked to secondguess the scientific 
judgments of the epa the appeals court said we cannot say that 
the epas assessment of the scientific evidence was unreasonable 
the case is maine vs epa 88684 
