<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to review the 
stiff fines imposed against four yonkers ny councilmen for 
defying a federal judges order to adopt a housing desegregation 
plan 
the justices said they will study arguments that the judge 
exceeded his power in imposing the contemptofcourt fines 
the case attracted national attention last summer as the defiant 
councilmen were threatened with jail as well as fines and the city 
faced possible bankruptcy for refusing to obey us district judge 
leonard sands order 
faced with massive layoffs of city workers the city council 
voted last sept 10 to comply with sands order to build 1000 
lowcost homes to desegregate middleclass areas of the city 
but yonkers located just north of new york city had to pay 
819000 in fines each of the four councilmen was ordered to pay 
3500 for being in contempt of a desegregation order issued the 
previous aug 2 
the case stemmed from a justice department lawsuit begun in the 
carter administrations waning days in 1980 
sand in 1985 ruled that yonkers officials intentionally and 
unlawfully promoted racial segregation through the citys housing 
and school policies 
he ordered the city to desegregate the school system and build 
subsidized housing in predominantly white sections of the city 
city officials agreed in january 1988 to build 200 units and make 
plans for 600 more they later sought to back out of the agreement 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals last august said sand acted 
properly in holding the city and the four councilmen in contempt 
after the council voted 43 against a package of financial 
incentives designed to attract development of 800 low and 
moderateincome homes 
sand imposed fines against the city starting at 100 a day and 
doubling daily until officials lived up to their desegregation the 
appeals court put a cap of 1 million a day on the fines and upheld 
the judges 500aday fine for each councilman 
the councilmens jail terms were blocked temporarily by a supreme 
court order last september and the threat of imprisonment was 
lifted after the council relented and adopted the desegregation plan 
the four councilmen are nicholas v longo edward j fagan jr 
peter chema and vice mayor henry spallone 
the appeals court said the four are not protected by legislative 
immunity against the contempt order and fines because the city 
government previously consented to abide by a courtapproved 
agreement to desegregate 
no litigant least of all public officials sworn to uphold the 
constitution of the united states may be permitted to avoid 
compliance with solemn commitments they have made in a consent 
judgment entered by a federal district court to remedy 
constitutional violations the appeals court said 
the 2nd circuit court also rejected arguments that the 
freespeech rights of the councilmen were violated they remain 
free to express their views on all aspects of housing in yonkers 
but not to violate lawful court orders the appeals court said 
the appeals court also turned back the citys argument in 
effect one made in behalf of the city treasury and the taxpayers 
that it was powerless to compel the council members to adopt the 
housing desegregation plan 
the city cannot view itself as an entity separate from the city 
council for purposes of complying with the consent judgment to 
build the homes the appeals court said 
the justices today granted the appeals of the four councilmen but 
rejected an appeal filed in behalf of the city 
the cases are spallone vs us 88854 yonkers vs us 
88855 chema vs us 88856 and longo vs us 88870 
