<TEXT>
the supreme court today left intact a 90000 
libel award won against six american newspapers serving 
koreanamerican readers 
the justices without comment turned away arguments that the 
newspapers should not have been legally liable for accurately 
reporting an announcement made by a south korean government agency 
at issue was the scope of the legal immunity a news organization 
enjoys when accurately and fairly reporting about government reports 
or public proceedings despite their defamatory nature 
in the case acted on today the 4th us circuit court of appeals 
ruled that the socalled fair report privilege does not apply to 
reporting about acts by foreign governments 
two intelligence agencies of the south korean government issued a 
62page press release on sept 9 1985 announcing the 
disruption of two north korean spy rings operating in the united 
states and west germany 
the government agencies said one of the spy rings was run by 
students at western illinois university and identified changsin 
lee as one north korean agent 
lee who emigrated to this country from south korea in 1975 and 
graduated from western illinois in 1984 now lives in new york city 
he recently became a us citizen 
lee sued six newspapers and a virginia television station in 
federal court in virginia alleging that their reports libeled him 
by reiterating the south korean governments announcement 
a federal trial judge threw out the suit noting that virginia 
law includes a fair report privilege the judge said that lee could 
not win his libel suit because he could not prove the newspapers and 
television station acted with malice 
the 4th circuit court reinstated lees suit last june 20 ruling 
that the fair report privilege should not have been invoked 
the appeals court by a 21 vote said the privilege never should 
apply to a news organizations reporting on information received 
from foreign governments 
because we find that foreign governments are not necessarily 
more reliable than domestic nonofficial sources we are not willing 
to enlarge the scope of the fair report privilege to include 
information from such governments the appeals court said 
it added some countries may take advantage of our liberal 
first amendment rights in order maliciously to defame or carelessly 
and without adequate inquiry excoriate private parties 
the ruling meant lee could win his libel suit against the news 
organizations by proving the government report about him was false 
and made negligently 
the ruling also cleared the way for a libel trial in which a 
jury earlier this year awarded a total of 90000 against the six 
newspapers the television station wnvctv was found not to have 
libeled lee 
in the appeal acted on today lawyers for the six newspapers 
argued that the fair report privilege for reporting on foreign 
goverments sometimes should be available 
the newspapers are the korea herald the donga iblo joongang 
ilbo the chosun ilbo the korea times and the sae gae shinbo 
the case is the donga ilbo v lee 881145 
