<TEXT>
the federal government is considering helping 
pay the costs of programs that assist government workers in their 
efforts to quit smoking officials said monday 
if the rule takes effect the government will be following in the 
footsteps of many businesses which have combined antismoking 
programs with workplace rules banning tobacco according to the 
american cancer society 
the federal office of personnel management is circulating the 
proposal which would allow agencies use available funds for such 
programs officials announced 
smoking cessation programs particularly for federal employees 
are long overdue this is a positive step opm director constance 
horner said in a statement ms horner is a former smoker 
the plan would require that employees get advance approval for 
reimbursement in the antismoking programs 
the regulation is being prepared in the wake of a ruling by the 
comptroller general that funding could be approved because smoking 
is a major contributing cause of illnesses such as cancer heart 
disease and emphysema 
the growth of both government and business rules banning smoking 
in many workplaces has spurred many companies to contribute to 
programs to help workers quit said joann schellenbech assistant 
vice president for media relations at the cancer society in new york 
we think its an excellent idea our surveys show that most 
smokers want to quit and need something to help them do that the 
incentive of having program paid for may make a difference she 
said 
costs for the programs range widely she said from free clinics 
conducted by nonprofit groups to 200 and more for morestructured 
systems 
the expense of the antismoking efforts can be justified by the 
savings in insurance costs cuts in sick time and reductions in lost 
productivity she said 
brennan dawson of the tobacco institute said that organization 
would have no immediate comment on the proposal 
