the state assembly approved legislation 
monday to restore the death penalty in new york as the bills chief 
sponsor predicted the chamber would for the first time override a 
promised veto by gov mario cuomo 
a successful override later this year in the 
democraticcontrolled assembly would clear the way for the electric 
chair to be put back into use in the nations second largest state 
california already has the death penalty 
the assembly approved the deathpenalty measure 9748 after an 
emotionally charged debate lasting more than five hours 
the senate which passed the legislation last month is expected 
to override the veto as it has several times in the past a 
successful override in the assembly would restore the death penalty 
new yorks electric chair last used in 1963 has been sitting 
unused at greenhaven state prison in stormville since capital 
punishment in the state was eliminated by a series of court rulings 
the chair the first in the world has already been used to execute 
695 people since its introduction in 1890 
two death penalty supporters were absent from the assembly on 
monday had they been present there would have been 99 yes 
votes in the 150member assembly a veto override requires 100 votes 
cuomo has promised to veto the bill making it the seventh year 
in a row the democratic governor has quashed capital punishment 
legislation 
assemblyman vincent graber the bills chief assembly sponsor 
predicted he would have the extra vote required by the time the 
override attempt comes later this year 
state lawmakers have approved death penalty legislation in the 
last 12 years but cuomo and former gov hugh carey repeatedly 
vetoed it 
graber a buffalo area democrat closed in on the 100vote 
override margin when longtime death penalty opponent edward abramson 
of new york city also a democrat announced he would vote for 
grabers bill 
abramson citing the highly publicized assassination last year in 
his district of police officer edward bryne by associates of a drug 
dealer said a poll of his constituents found that 73 percent 
supported the death penalty 
the vote came less than a week after a federal narcotics agent 
and a city policeman were shot to death in separate incidents in new 
york city 
before the debate about 150 antideath penalty demonstrators 
many from a hutterite religious community near kingston gathered 
outside the assembly chamber and sang such traditional protest songs 
as we shall overcome 
