ned doyle a cofounder of doyle dane bernbach 
inc one of the nations largest advertising agencies died sunday 
at his manhattan home the agency announced monday he was 86 
the announcement did not give the cause of doyles death 
when the agency was formed in 1949 doyle was named executive 
vice president in charge of account services he became chairman of 
its executive committee in 1967 when the company had grown to 
become the nations eighth largest advertising firm 
doyle remained on the agencys board of directors after his 
retirement in 1969 in 1986 doyle dane bernbach merged with two 
other large agencies bbdo worldwide and needham harper worldwide 
to form omnicom group inc one of the worlds largest advertising 
corporations 
doyles blunt comments to coworkers and clients led many in the 
advertising field to refer to him as the man with the sandpaper 
charm 
one ddb employee once said of doyle he is the roughest 
toughest softest man i know and i suspect the first two are 
putons 
doyle got his first taste of the advertising world as a magazine 
space salesman a job he held while attending fordham law school at 
night 
although he passed his bar examination he never practiced law 
in those days after you passed the bar you went to work in a 
law office for 10 a week i was making 75 a week selling space i 
couldnt afford to quit he explained 
doyle served as western and eastern manager for cosmopolitan 
magazine in the 1930s and in 1936 he became the first advertising 
manager for a new magazine look 
just before world war ii he went to work for good housekeeping 
magazine after the japanese attacked pearl harbor he tried to 
enlist in the us marines but was rejected because he was too old 
for voluntary military service he was 39 at the time 
doyle persisted and enlisted in 1942 because of his good 
housekeeping background the marines appointed him a mess officer 
he protested and within three weeks was reassigned and became an 
intelligence officer serving in the pacific as a captain 
after the war he joined grey advertising and in 1949 he and 
greys creative director bill bernbach decided to create their own 
agency along with maxwell dane who was running his own small ad 
agency the result was ddb 
doyle is survived by three children and four grandchildren 
