<DOCNO> AP890306-0208 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
caterina cornaro was a pawn in superpower 
intrigues five centuries ago but she ruled as queen of cyprus for 
almost 16 years and won a lasting reputation as a fascinating 
renaissance personality 
caterina a venetian aristocrat inspired dozens of portraits as 
a darkeyed beauty a string of biographies and five operas 
including one by the italian composer gaetano donizetti 
her life story reads like a pulp romance starting with a 
shortlived marriage at 18 to james the bastard king of cyprus and 
ending with retirement near venice presiding over a glittering salon 
of poets painters and musicians 
but a new book published to mark the 500th anniversary of 
caterinas enforced abdication in 1489 avoids depicting her as a 
tragic heroine 
instead she comes across as a tough survivor maneuvering to 
stay alive in an maelstrom of violence and political treachery 
between greeks and italians on this east mediterranean island 
according to one of the three contributors to caterina cornaro 
queen of cyprus the chroniclers references to her as la bella 
donna the beautiful lady probably were inaccurate 
she must have had what we would call charisma but i dont 
think she could be considered beautiful more a woman of 
character terence mullaly a british art critic and renaissance 
specialist said in an interview 
she was certainly hardheaded and realistic and not the sad 
deposed queen of the sentimental legend 
mullaly said that none of the portraits of caterina as a young 
woman were definitely contemporary the only one that dates from her 
lifetime by the renowned venetian painter gentile bellini shows a 
plump matron with shrewd eyes and a capable air he said 
caterina rose to fame when she sailed to cyprus in september 1472 
to marry james a ruthless but popular king who seized the throne 
from his halfsister charlotte the legitimate heir 
but james died suddenly nine months later apparently of 
dysentery and so did caterinas infant son both in suspicious 
circumstances according to joachim g joachim a cypriot historian 
who also contributed to the book 
im convinced that both james and his son were poisoned and 
the venetians are the prime suspects joachim said in an interview 
the historian who researched caterinas life in libraries around 
europe added it was their favored method of assassination they 
had professional poisoners on the state payroll and they 
benefited most from james death 
cyprus had been ruled for centuries by frenchspeaking kings 
descended from the crusaders who fought in the holy land the island 
was coveted by egypt turkey and venice as an important trading post 
for merchants dealing in silks and spices from the orient 
caterina succeeded to the throne but she was hemmed in by her 
venetian relatives and advisers who accused her of spending 
extravagantly they also blocked her plans to marry prince alonzo of 
naples when she was 34 and he was 22 
caterina fought back writing letters to venice complaining that 
her counsellors spoke to her rudely and failed to consult her on 
financial and judicial issues 
in one letter she begged the doge of venice to strictly enforce 
legislation protecting cypriot peasants from being kidnapped and 
forced to row venetian galleys 
she also complained she was not allowed to dine royally in public 
attended by young noblemen but was permitted only a small table and 
two maids to serve her 
but in the face of a growing threat from ottoman turkey caterina 
was finally persuaded to abdicate in 1489 and make a gift of cyprus 
to the venetian republic 
in return she got a pension of 8000 ducats a year for life and 
sovereignty over the small hill town of asolo 33 miles from venice 
histories say 8000 ducats was a comfortable royal stipend for that 
time according to calculations based on the amount of gold in a 
ducat the stipend would be worth around 450000 today 
the venetians were the alltime masters of diplomacy joachim 
said they knew when to act and caterina knew when she had to 
give in 
in asolo and her three other homes in the veneto caterina 
sponsored theatrical performances and concerts and entertained the 
leading intellectuals of the day 
but her practical streak emerged too she rebuilt much of asolo 
organized a lending bank and tax reforms and even imported grain 
from cyprus during a famine 
caterina died in 1510 and was buried in venice the venetians 
held on to cyprus until 1570 when it was captured by the turks 
caterina was an extraordinary person she deserves to be 
known for the character she really was not the legend said iro 
hunt who coedited the book with her husband a former british high 
commissioner to cyprus 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a muddy field near the berlin wall a young pole 
looks furtively about and pulls a bottle of vodka out of a plastic 
bag 
five marks you can have he says 
he motions to a fox fur coat on a hanger clipped to button on his 
shirt a bargain for 30 marks 17 he says 
if he sells four bottles of vodka at five marks 270 each or 
the fur coat he will have earned himself the equivalent of about a 
months salary in poland 
across town in the fashionable zehlendorf district three poles 
are painting the interior of a handsome turnofthecentury villa 
for the unbeatable price of 400 marks 220 
you couldnt get a union painter to even look at the place for 
that price said the homeowner speaking only on condition of 
anonymity 
city officials estimate that as many as 4000 poles sell goods or 
their labor illegally in west berlin now that entry into the city 
has been eased for them many advertize in the citys newspapers 
offering to do home repair work and odd jobs at prices many west 
berliners find hard to resist 
thousands of poles are also turning up on weekends at a 
fleamarket to sell everything from baby clothes to superbly crafted 
amber necklaces for hard currency such as marks and dollars 
with the polish economy in shambles the vendors say hard 
currency has become the only means to acquire quality goods and food 
items in short supply it also offers the opportunity for staggering 
profits on the black market currency exchange at home 
without hard currency you cant get anything thats any good 
said a 30yearold man from gdansk who drove through the night to 
be at the market when it opened at 5 am 
he was among a record 8000 poles who jammed a field in the 
kreuzberg district of the city on a recent weekend 
thousands of west berliners jostled through the mud to inspect 
shoes clothing household goods and food the grocery goods 
displayed in open suitcases and car trunks ranged from heaps of 
polish sausage to tins of russian caviar at dumping prices 
many poles at the market earn enough west german marks in a 
weekend to support them for several months 
ten marks on the black market in poland will get you up to 
20000 zloty or almost as much as a pension said a middleaged 
man from krakow who was selling crystal goblets from the trunk of 
his car 
a companion who said he came from warsaw added i buy goods 
in poland for 1000 zloty that i can sell here for 200 marks with 
those 200 marks i can get 400000 zloty on the black market in 
poland we can live for six months on that 
a polish house painter who asked not to be named said he could 
earn a years wages from three months work in west berlin 
under new regulations that went into effect jan 1 poles do not 
need visas to enter west berlin and are allowed to stay as long as 
three months 
however they come as tourists and are prohibited from engaging 
in commercial enterprises 
so far west berlin police have cracked down only on vendors 
illegally selling heavily taxed items such as cigarettes furs 
jewelry and alcohol 
west berlin police said that on one day alone authorities seized 
11 liters of vodka 28000 cigarettes 360 grams about 12 ounces 
of caviar and two fur coats fourteen polish vendors were charged 
with violations of import tax laws 
six poles were arrested in february and expelled after they were 
caught working illegally in the city 
customs checks have also been stepped up and the west berlin 
senate has ordered that poles caught smuggling goods be immediately 
expelled and the offense noted in their passports 
but customs officials say tourists are allowed to bring in goods 
worth up to 100 marks 54 for personal use and it is often 
impossible to prove that the goods are intended for sale 
there are too many of them and too few of us said an 
exasperated customs officer as as he made his way down a row of 
sputtering polish fiats and vans at checkpoint charley at the berlin 
wall 
around the corner where 45 cars packed to the roofs with goods 
waited for custom inspectection deals were already flourishing 
a west berliner walked away with a porcelain tea set for 50 marks 
27 three times less than the department store price 
</TEXT>
