editors note edward pembroke oversees a most unusual 
performance in a most unlikely setting hes been doing it for 48 
years and spectators still wonder why they find it so amusing he 
knows why 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a few days before his 9th birthday edward 
pembroke dared to try every boys ultimate adventure he ran away 
and joined the circus 
his purpose he says was to escape violin lessons not to become 
a performer 
yet today a few days before his 80th birthday on march 22 
edward pembroke is still going strong as the raucous ringmaster of 
the oldest established permanent floating animal act in memphis 
perhaps in america and certainly one of the most charming 
hes the peabody duck man 
i swear he was saying the other day scratching his gray 
head i still dont understand why people like it so much 
you saw em saw how they behave they laugh and clap and cheer 
and take pictures theyve been doing that for the 48 years since 
ive been here and were doing it before that so im told i dont 
understand it i just do it twice a day 
edward pembroke understands more than he lets on the applause 
recognizes the unlikely setting for the performance and edward 
pembrokes sense of showmanship makes the most of it 
picture this 
at midmorning the grand and gilded lobby of the peabody hotel 
begins to fill the bar opens and the tinkle of ice in thin glasses 
mingles with the chatter of expectant guests 
at 1045 am the bell captain rolls a red carpet from the 
elevators brass door 50 feet to the base of the fountain in the 
center of the lobby beneath handpainted beams and wroughtiron 
chandeliers he places a threestep redcarpeted staircase up to the 
lip of the fountain 
the fountain is of carved travertine marble four marble cherubs 
support a huge marble bowl of fresh water overflowing into an 
octagonal marble pool above the bowl a marble pot overflows with 
fresh flowers when it comes to gilt and grandeur the peabody is 
not known to stint 
at the stroke of 11 a loudspeaker announces solemnly your 
attention please ladies and gentlemen the peabody ducks 
spectators crowd into position along both sides of the red 
carpet the loudspeaker strikes up stars and stripes forever 
all eyes turn to the polished brass elevator doors 
they open with a flourish and edward pembroke in a voice like a 
trumpet cries lets go ducks 
out they come a mallard drake leading a fourhen harem pembroke 
swaggers behind them in a burgundy and black uniform carrying a 
stick like a field marshal 
down the red carpet they waddle up the red stairs over the 
marble ledge flapping and quacking into their elegant pond 
cheers laughter flashbulbs 
edward pembroke has devoted more than half his long life to this 
twicedaily task the duck parade will be repeated in reverse 
precisely at 5 pm when they return to their penthouse palace and 
he appears more than content in his role 
ive done lots of other things in my life he said some 
ill tell you about some i wont but the ducks are important to 
the peabody and im proud to be the one to see after them i never 
saw any reason to change jobs 
indeed edward pembroke has done other things chatting with him 
you get the impression that the ones he wont tell you about 
outnumber the ones he will 
when he fled his home in reading pa in 1918 and the circus 
people adopted him they gave him a job delivering the mail for 
428 a week 
that way i got to know all of them about half of them couldnt 
read or write both black and white people i did that for them 
sometimes wed get a notice that a sheriff was waiting for one of 
them in the next town so of course id warn them about that i 
never turned in anybody 
</TEXT>
