<TEXT>
he stayed with the circus 13 years until he was 22 moving on to 
more responsible jobs of every sort including animal handling 
ducks would prove to be a pushover 
i left the circus because the train was in a wreck coming out 
of florida i was hurt pretty bad and had to stay behind 
when he recovered pembroke found jobs where he could a period 
in his life he recalls with a grin but few specifics 
by inclination he drifted toward the company of entertainers in 
chicago he drove the bus for the count basie band in memphis he 
palled around with blues man wc handy and other beale street 
denizens and in 1940 landed a job at the peabody two blocks off 
beale as bell captain 
the peabody with various face lifts over the years has been a 
southern institution since 1869 and is listed on the national 
register of historic places the saying is that the mississippi 
delta begins in the lobby of the peabody hotel and ends on catfish 
row in vicksburg miss 
by the time edward pembroke arrived the ducks were an established 
peabody trademark 
the story is that back in 1932 the hotels general manager 
returned from a duck hunting trip with three live decoys which were 
legal then as a prank he put them in the fountain theyve been 
there ever since 
now duck imprints show up on everything imprintable the hotels 
soap ash urns swizzle sticks chocolates that appear on 
turneddown beds one of its dining rooms is named dux another 
mallards the only place ducks do not appear is on the menu 
thats forbidden 
the ducks were here when i came pembroke recalls but they 
didnt do the march then that started with me the duck palace is 
new too 
thats where the ducks live in regal splendor on the roof where 
people party and dance in the summertime 
the palace is a large carpeted cage with a bed chamber 
painted purple and gold trays of cracked corn are handy so is a 
6footwide pool sweetened daily with fresh lettuce from the 
kitchen a flower garden a 24foot mural of trees and waterfowl 
and a magnificent view of the mississippi river 
it is a duck camelot and must look inviting to less privileged 
ducks migrating along the mississippi flyway 
oh it does says pembroke every spring and fall some of 
them land on the roof i shoo em off 
he also shoos off the peabody ducks every four months 
all that high living makes them so fat they wobble not waddle 
wobble so we replace them they dont get much exercise swimming 
around in the fountain and they cant fly 
they cant 
i clip one wing otherwise theyd be flying all around the 
lobby 
