<TEXT>
still looming over scotlands capital 
city today is edinburgh castle a turreted ancient fortress on a 
hill that has succumbed to english invasions since the 7th century 
its symbolic of how scotland nearly 300 years after its union 
with england feels dominated by its southern neighbor which sets 
the direction for its economy not always many scots feel the 
most desirable one 
scotlands lack of control over its own economic affairs is a big 
issue north of the border particularly now that a sharp rise in 
interest rates is threatening a slow belated recovery in the 
scottish economy 
the feeling that scotland has fallen behind england that its 
economy has been battered by nearly a decade of prime minister 
margaret thatchers policies makes for some potent antigovernment 
and antienglish sentiment in scotland 
mrs thatcher has pushed interest rates up 55 percentage points 
to 13 percent in five months to curb inflation which has 
accelerated to a 75percent annual rate this among other things 
could raise the value of the british pound and hurt exports on 
which the country depends heavily 
the harmful effects of dampening could be worse on the scottish 
economy just because youre cutting the recovery off just at the 
point where it should continue to be growing said jim walker an 
economist at the royal bank of scotland 
the backlash also fueled by strong opposition to the 
governments property tax reform has revived scottish nationalist 
sentiment and a heated debate over whether scotland should keep the 
status quo or seek selfgovernment 
the tax reform known as the poll tax takes effect in scotland 
in april and is based on the number of people in a home rather than 
the value of the property property values tend to be lower in 
scotland 
there is a great struggle of minds in the people of scotland 
said jim sillars a scottish national party member who won a 
stunning election victory in govan in november ousting a labor 
party member and reviving his partys fortunes 
opinion polls consistently find 80 percent of scots would prefer 
a moderate degree of selfgovernment but the scottish national 
partys call for outright independence attracts only minority 
support 
now the nationalists have come up with a new formula 
independence within europe whereby scotland would become 
independent but retain an association with england by joining the 
european economic community 
a recent opinion poll put support for the scottish national party 
at 28 percent double its strength in the june 1987 general 
election it stands in second place after the labor party which has 
a 41percent approval rating conservatives are third at 20 percent 
of scotlands 72 seats in the 650member house of commons in 
london 49 are labor 10 are conservative four are nationalist and 
the rest are held by centrist parties 
a referendum in 1979 failed to win the necessary majority for 
devolution or selfgovernment within the united kingdom scotland 
has always had its own church presbyterian as opposed to anglican 
in england its own currency and its own legal and educational 
systems but critical decisions such as interest rate increases are 
usually taken in whitehall the seat of government in london 400 
miles south 
most scots are staunch socialists mrs thatcher a fervent 
capitalist has been fighting to eradicate socialism from britain 
she is also a firm believer in maintaining the union between 
england and scotland 
this government remains committed to the union as committed as 
ever she said in a recent speech in scotland and it is in the 
union that we have flourished and found strength 
nationalists have long accused the english of fostering 
scotlands kiltandbagpipe identity as a diversion from the real 
issues of nationhood 
now they talk of scotland being englished as more and more 
positions of power in the scottish cultural bureaucracy fall to 
english appointees 
the governments scottish secretary malcolm rifkind says scots 
have benefited greatly from the government which spent 2676 pounds 
4683 per capita in scotland compared with 2162 pounds 3784 
overall in the last fiscal year 
scottishborn rifkind a cabinet minister says government policy 
is not to put more pounds into peoples pockets but to make them 
take the initiative 
in a speech he urged scots search out the opportunities do 
not just respond to those put on the plate before you 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890306-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
scotland was united with england in 1707 its 51 million people 
are about onetenth of britains population and its 30000 square 
miles represent about onethird of the kingdom 
its economy now depends on services and high technology rather 
than basic industries largely because it has managed to attract 
outside investment principally american investors in the 
electronics industry who have created a silicon glen in central 
scotland 
the north sea oil industry has been recovering from a sharp 
downturn in 1986 scotlands huge financial services sector is 
growing a bit 
the historic industries of whisky salmon fishing and woolens 
have modernized and are thriving partly by targeting the upscale 
market 
unemployment at 103 percent is finally falling and scottish 
businessmen are looking confident 
generally the scene is quite good said john davidson 
scottish director of the confederation of british industry 
the scottish economy grew an estimated 35 percent last year 
compared with 45 percent in britain overall it should grow as much 
as 3 percent this year faster for a change than britain said 
gordon hughes a university of edinburgh professor 
but not everybodys assessment is sunny and many problems 
remain sillars the nationalist said theres a lot of economic 
anxiety around in scotland 
scotland has been painfully wrenched from its dependence on its 
declining heavy industries and its job losses which have been 
exacerbated by mrs thatchers refusal to use taxpayers money to 
rescue ailing industries 
scotlands unemployment rate remains 33 percentage points higher 
than the british average of 7 percent 
the number of people employed in steel shipbuilding coal and 
the heavy engineering industries has fallen in 30 years from 300000 
to about 50000 davidson said 
there is an incredibly strong attachment to what represents 
scottish industrial heritage hughes said there is an enormous 
reluctance to come to terms with that and change that 
critics complain that inward investment is creating a branch 
economy based on lowskilled assembly jobs 
the problem with scotland is that we dont have new 
indigenous industry said martin gregson a scottish entrepreneur 
many of the jobs created by the inward investment go to women 
davidson said 
i think it has a very distinct effect on the way scotland 
lives were a very chauvinistic society he said 
strongly presbyterian scotland prides itself on its respect for 
authority its moral standards work ethic and collective spirit 
scotland also is concerned about outside takeovers of its 
