<TEXT>
a michigan law that required 7 percent of all 
state contracts be awarded to minorityowned businesses and 5 
percent to businesses owned by women was unconstitutional the 
supreme court ruled today 
the justices without issuing any written opinion upheld a 
federal appeals courts invalidation of the law 
in a jan 23 decision the high court itself struck down a 
similar affirmative action plan that set aside 30 percent of all 
city construction contracts in richmond va for minorityowned 
businesses 
in that ruling the justices made it far more difficult for local 
governments and by extension state governments to impose strict 
racial quotas as part of affirmative action plans 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals said the michigan program 
enacted in 1980 was unlawful because there was inadequate evidence 
of past discrimination by the state against minorities and women 
state officials have relied upon certain conclusory historical 
resumes of unrelated legislative enactments and proposed enactments 
executive reports and a statefunded private study conducted in 
1974 the appeals court said this documentation is not 
reflective of discriminatory action by the state of michigan 
the appeals court said there was little if any probative 
evidence of discrimination against minority groups and it said 
evidence of discrimination against women is nonexistent 
the minority groups covered by the program are blacks hispanics 
orientals eskimos and american indians 
state officials said the quota figures were based on the 
percentage of businesses in the state owned by minorities and women 
the setasides were challenged by various contractors doing 
business with the state led by the michigan road builders 
association 
the supreme court in 1980 upheld a federal law that set aside 10 
percent of federal contracts for minority owned businesses 
the case acted on today is milliken vs michigan road builders 
871860 
</TEXT>
