<TEXT>
the supreme court today reinstated a challenge 
to a miami affirmative action plan requiring 5 percent participation 
of businesses owned by women or minorities in building a rail 
transit system 
the justices by a 54 vote ordered a lower court to reconsider 
its dismissal of the challenge in light of their jan 23 decision 
striking down a similar affirmative action set aside program in 
richmond va 
justices william j brennan thurgood marshall harry a blackmun 
and john paul stevens voted to leave intact the miami affirmative 
action plan 
the richmond plan required that 30 percent of all public works 
contracts go to minorityowned businesses 
the miami plan was challenged by a construction company that 
submitted the lowest bid on the project but was rejected for lack of 
minority participation 
the project involved construction of an electrified third rail 
for the citys transit system which is run by metropolitan dade 
county officials the construction is financed with 80 percent 
federal funds 
dade county awarded the contract in 1979 to transit products 
inc which submitted the second lowest bid of 837 million the 
low bid 808 million was submitted by hk porter company inc 
county officials required that 5 percent of the work be farmed 
out to minority subcontractors unless the main contractor could show 
it made every reasonable effort but failed to get minority 
participation 
porter said it was unable to arrange minority participation 
the corporation said it has a plant in chicago that would 
assemble the electrified third rail and that only four items from 
outside sources would be needed to complete the project the firm 
said no minority firms produced any of those items 
after its bid was rejected the company sued for 15 million in 
damages the firm said the dade county setaside plan is a form of 
reverse discrimination that violates its constitutional rights 
a federal judge threw out the porter lawsuit and the 11th us 
circuit court of appeals upheld that ruling 
the appeals court citing key supreme court rulings on 
affirmative action said the miami plan is justified by a federal 
law mandating minority participation in federally financed public 
works projects 
congress in 1978 passed the surface transportation assistance act 
appropriating money for highways and mass transit the law without 
setting specific percentages called for participation of minority 
business enterprises to alleviate past discrimination against women 
blacks hispanics and other minorities 
the 11th circuit court said dade county was not 
constitutionally required to make additional findings of past 
discrimination regarding the awarding of this contract congress was 
concerned about a national problem its findings provide adequate 
support for such local projects 
the appeals court conceded it was troubled by a lack of evidence 
to support the 5 percent figure for the miami project but the 
appeals court said the supreme court had upheld higher percentages 
for minority participation 
the appeals court also noted that porter failed to show it made 
every reasonable effort to get minority participation from 
subcontractors to support its bid 
in urging the justices to reject porters appeal dade county 
officials noted that the federal regulations at issue in the case 
acted on today were amended by a 1982 law 
the new law changes the concept of minorityowned businesses to 
require 10 percent participation in federally supported projected of 
small businesses owned by socially and economically disadvantaged 
individuals 
the case is porter vs metropolitan dade county 871001 
</TEXT>
