<TEXT>
on reviewing the monthly housing statistics you 
might think that one of todays most popular participant activities 
is moving preparing to move or thinking about moving 
it isnt quite true it is true nevertheless that real estate and 
housing markets have been particularly busy in recent months and 
years in spite of foreboding by economists and despite rising 
prices and interest rates 
january housing starts soared to 169 million units 170000 
units higher than in december 1988 and 310000 thousand higher than 
in december 1987 singlefamily resales last year reached 363 
million units the highest since 1978 
but while such statistics are impressive and to some extent 
unexpected there is an aspect of the housing market that is even 
more active remodeling that is seems to have become the national 
pastime 
while final figures arent in the national association of home 
builders already has declared that remodeling and fixup 
expenditures last year exceeded 100 billion for the first time 
double the amount spent five years earlier 
while the exact amount for the year hasnt been determined it is 
known that in the first three quarters the annual rate was better 
than 102 billion and that preliminary indications were for a strong 
fourth quarter 
the spending rise has been what economists tend to call 
dramatic after varying between about 45 billion and 49 
billion in the four years from 1980 through 1983 the total soared 
to 698 billion in 1984 
it has risen without interruption since then to 803 billion in 
1985 912 billion in 1986 and 941 billion in 1987 
even when adjusted for inflation says kenneth klein a tulsa 
remodeler and chairman of the nahb remodelers council this huge 
increase makes the remodeling industry the fastest growing sector 
of the construction industry 
whether growth will continue is questionable because almost all 
segments of housing markets are cyclical the nahb expects growth of 
four to six percent for the next three to five years or little more 
than the inflation rate 
some nonhousing people wouldnt be surprised however to see 
the trend continue especially if the cost of new housing continues 
to rise they point to these factors as contributing to the 
remodeling and repair statistics 
the rising cost of housing which often makes it more 
advantageous to remodel than move new houses often absorb all of 
the old equity remodeling may leave some for other purposes 
the desire to remain in mature communities with good schools and 
desirable amenities rather than moving to new communities with 
prospects of higher taxes for new schools and municipal improvements 
equity growth and growing access to that equity through 
taxadvantaged loans 
convenience as well as savings anyone who has moved recently 
knows it can be costly for moving expenses setup costs lawyers 
new mortgages and the points that accompany them 
there may be inconvenience in either instance moving or 
remodeling but in remodeling you can at least stay put amid the 
noise confusion and dirt 
according to an nahb survey the top remodeling activities in 
1987 were room additions which accounted for 255 percent of all 
remodeling and kitchen remodeling 202 percent complete 
rehabilitation accounted for 79 percent 
as many homeowners might guess the major expenditures by type of 
work were painting plumbing and roofing with heating and central 
air conditioning not far behind luxuries such as swimming pools 
were far down the list 
</TEXT>
