<TEXT>
the us electronics trade deficit 
with the world shrank about 25 percent in 1988 to 96 billion but 
the deficit with japan grew 2 percent the american electronics 
association reported monday 
us exports increased more than 28 percent to 58 billion from 
452 billion in 1987 while imports increased 17 percent to 676 
billion from 58 billion 
us electronics companies exports to japan shot up but a small 
percentage increase in imports was still enough to cause the deficit 
to swell 
the electronics trade deficit with japan grew to 205 billion 
from 201 billion us exports to japan grew more than 43 percent 
to 63 billion in 1988 from 44 billion in 1987 imports from 
japan increased 94 percent to 268 billion 
this significant reduction in our trade deficit with the world 
is the result of a surge in us electronics exports said j 
richard iverson aea president and chief executive officer 
unfortunately the same progress wasnt achieved with our trade 
problems with japan he added the japanese electronics industry 
must realize that trade is a twoway street and that the open 
markets in the united states must be matched by the same in japan 
the fourthquarter us electronics trade deficit with the world 
decreased by almost 20 percent to 30 billion from 37 billion in 
1987 exports rose to 157 billion from 127 billion and imports 
to 186 billion from 164 billion 
the us electronics trade deficit with japan for electronics 
products and services slowed its rate of growth in the 1988 fourth 
quarter to 15 percent to 56 billion from 55 billion us 
exports to japan improved to 18 billion in the 1988 quarter from 
13 billion in 1987 and imports from japan rose to 74 billion 
from 69 billion 
the aea represents more than 3500 companies in the united states 
</TEXT>
